I saw I forgot to answer to this. I don't think that makes sense, because the model for what is efficient in a circuit is very different from what is efficient in normal programming.

Montgomery representation helps you to avoid a trial division to compute the quotient and remainder when reducing a multiplication result mod p. In a zk circuit however, you don't do a trial division. You just witness the quotient and remainder, and then assert the equation `x = q*p + r`. so, computing the quotient and remainder have 0 impact on the circuit. No point in optimizing 0 constraints.
Thanks for the answer

messages.content: Shouldn't I use bigint in any place?
Can I use Field3 as a provable type?
Is it okay to write a constructor of Fq by using Field3 instead of bigint?
I answered your issue by suggesting a new pattern

> Shouldn't I use bigint in any place?
you can use it to compute constants that become hard-coded in your circuit, you can't use it to convert to/from Fields in your code.

A good rule of thumb is to just compile a circuit which calls your methods. It will fail if you convert a Field to a bigint in-circuit.
Tip: Always have an actual example that creates a proof, as early as possible - that way you avoid patterns that won't work.
